post_text:
Starting Tuesday, September 8th, Silsbee High School will begin distribution of Chromebooks to ALL face to face learners through their English Classes. Remote learners can exchange their Chromebooks starting Thursday, September 10th from 9am - 4pm in the front lobby. In order to receive a Chromebook, the following steps must be completed by both an SHS student and their parent/guardian.

‚Äì Watch the Chromebook Orientation Video
‚Äì Fill out the Orientation Form
‚Äì Fill out the Chromebook Parent Agreement Form
‚Äì $40.00 deposit required at SHS (cash, money order, or check)

The Orientation Video can be found by clicking About Us then Enrollment on the SHS website or found in the Remote Learners Hub on the district website.
Please check your spam or trash folder for an email with the Silsbee ISD Chromebook Agreement Form.

Keep in mind - students will NOT be able to check out a NEW Chromebook if they have not returned the older model Chromebook from last year.

Please contact SHS Administration if you have any questions or concerns.

post_text:
Due to the current forecast of the tropical systems in the Gulf of Mexico, Silsbee ISD will close on Tuesday, August 25 through Friday, August 28. District offices will reopen on August 31. The safety of our faculty, staff and their families is our highest priority, and this closure will allow many to prepare for the approaching storms.

Silsbee ISD will delay the start of school for students until Tuesday, September 1 to allow our staff to prepare for reopening classes.

At this time, the Silsbee varsity football game between the Tigers and Vidor Pirates is tentatively rescheduled for Saturday, August 29 at 6:00 p.m.

Silsbee Elementary Supply Dropoff will continue on Tuesday, August 25. Fourth grade from 8‚Äì10 a.m. and fifth grade from 10:15 a.m.‚Äì12:15 p.m.

We will continue to keep everyone informed through various channels including social media, and our local media outlets.

Please be safe and stay alert of all warnings.

Parents will be able to declare which educational learning pathway they would like their child to attend school for the 2020-2021 school year, which begins August 31, 2020. The two pathways will be On-Campus Learning and Remote Learning.

Once a student begins one of the the learning options, they will remain on this pathway through the six-week grading period. A student will be permitted to switch pathways at the beginning of the following grading period. A student who becomes ill may begin Remote Learning any time.

One form per student must be filled out. Please click the link to your respective campus.

post_text:
We apologize for calls not going through at Silsbee Middle School and Silsbee High School.

There is a high volume of phone calls at Silsbee Middle School and Silsbee High School regarding online registration for returning students. Anyone that does not have access to a Skyward Family Access account or has never had an account set up must call the respective campus. Please bear with us as we handle this large volume of phone calls and we will get to all of them as quickly as possible.

Online registration is for returning students only in middle school and high school.

Thank you for your patience.

post_text:
We have completed our Return-To-School Plan tentatively scheduled for August 12!

This tentative plan is being provided based on the COVID-19 public health crisis, as we understand it today. The pandemic and mandates from state and local officials also continue to evolve daily. Changes to this guidance may be restructured and implemented at any time, and through the course of the school year if necessary.

The complete plan can be found at https://docs.google.com/viewerng/viewer?url=https://www.silsbeeisd.org//cms/lib/TX01918305/Centricity/Domain/1116/Return+to+School+Plan+SISD.pdf

In addition to the guidelines for our 2020 SHS Graduation on Friday, all attendees are reminded of the following:

Each person must have a ticket (1 body = 1 ticket)

Every person, including graduates, must have a completed and signed Health Screening Form.

Only 2 car parking permits per graduate

No food or drink will be allowed in the stadium. Water only will be available for sale in the stadium.

No air horns or noise-makers will be allowed.

post_text:
Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to
free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application
instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who
are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year.

Click our website below for more details.

post_text:
Given the rapidly evolving situation with COVID-19, Silsbee ISD has extended its suspension of normal district operations through May 4 in an effort to support our state and federal agencies, Gov. Greg Abbott, and Hardin County Judge Wayne McDaniel. This suspension has been implemented to help slow the spread of the novel coronavirus, or COVID-19.

During this suspension, all Silsbee ISD athletic and school operated facilities, including outdoor facilities (tracks, fields, batting cages, playgrounds, etc.), will remain closed and not open to the public. Certain facilities may open when needed for student required services (student packet pickup, curbside meals, etc.). Otherwise, ALL facilities will remain closed.

post_text:
Silsbee Middle School students received hands-on experience of the Trail of Tears in Ms. Burris‚Äô history class. The Trail of Tears is known as the trek of nearly 125,000 Native Americans took in the 1830s, forced by the federal government to leave their homelands and walk thousands of miles to a specially designated territory across the Mississippi River. The students walked a small portion of the middle school campus to gather the idea of the terrain and conditions the Native Americans endured during this treacherous walk across the Southeastern U.S.
#WeAreSilsbee #ValuesSkillsConfidence

post_text: Silsbee High School students in Medical Terminology class were able to see how the four components of blood (plasma, red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets) make up our circulating blood volume through a hands-on lab using household items cheerios, red food coloring, marshmallows, oats, and water. Each student added the items to a water bottle, and then they were able to see how red blood cells pick up hemoglobin in the lungs and give "blood" its bright red color.
text: Silsbee High School students in Medical Terminology class were able to see how the four components of blood (plasma, red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets) make up our circulating blood volume through a hands-on lab using household items cheerios, red food coloring, marshmallows, oats, and water. Each student added the items to a water bottle, and then they were able to see how red blood cells pick up hemoglobin in the lungs and give "blood" its bright red color.

post_text:
We've been keeping it #FarmFreshTexas here at Silsbee ISD Food Services and Southwest Foodservice Excellence during October. We have been serving fresh local produce including oranges, apples, watermelon, romaine lettuce, cucumbers, bread, milk, and rice, and our lettuce and cucumbers are grown hydroponically at a Farm in Woodville, Texas.

Our Silsbee Elementary Food Service staff will vouch for this local freshness in our watermelons. #FarmFreshChallenge #FarmFreshTexas #WeAreSilsbee

post_text: Silsbee ISD schools will be open tomorrow and classes will resume under normal schedules. At this time, the district remains sound and functional. There are, however, limited drivers in transportation for tomorrow, so there will be an unusual amount of bus changes throughout all routes. Any buses that may arrive late to school will not impact any students‚Äô and tardies. Breakfast will also be provided to students that may arrive late. If there are any other changes to the school schedule, we will make proper announcements on social media, and on local news channels and radio.

post_text:
Silsbee High School HOSA students attended a Fall Leadership Conference at Tomball Memorial High School on Saturday, Oct. 19. The event was for all prospective and current HOSA members as a motivational tool, and to showcase the opportunities that HOSA offers to future health care professionals. Students attended several break-out sessions and gained leadership opportunities for future competitive events.

Students who attended were President Autumn Miller, Recorder Brianna Aiena, Secretary Emilie Williamson, and Member Faith Weems!

#WeAreSilsbee #ValuesSkillsConfidence #TeamWork

UPDATE: The suspect was apprehended and the lockout has been lifted. Our campuses are safe.

12:45 pm. ‚Äì Silsbee ISD has learned from Silsbee Police Department of a shooting that occurred near 8th Street in Silsbee. According to police, the suspect has not been apprehended. As a precaution to our students and staff, Silsbee Elementary and Laura Reeves Primary campuses have been placed on lockout. School resource officers are located at both campuses to ensure the safety of all.
